BIMData API API Reference

BIMData API is a tool to interact with your models stored on BIMData’s servers. Through the API, you can manage your projects, the clouds, upload your IFC files and manage them through endpoints.

API Endpoint
https://api-staging.bimdata.io/
Terms of Service: https://www.google.com/policies/terms/
Contact: contact@bimdata.io
Request Content-Types: application/json
Response Content-Types: application/json
Schemes: https
Version: v1

bcf

bcf

Get current user info

GET /bcf/2.1/current-user

Get current user info Required scopes: bcf:read

200 OK
SelfBcfUser
Response Example (200 OK) 
{
  "id": "string",
  "name": "string",
  "email": "string (email)"
}
bcf

Retrieve all BCF projects

GET /bcf/2.1/projects

Retrieve all BCF projects Required scopes: bcf:read

200 OK
BcfProject
type
BcfProject
Response Example (200 OK) 
[
  {
    "id": "integer",
    "name": "string"
  }
]
bcf

Retrieve a BCF project

GET /bcf/2.1/projects/{id}

Retrieve a BCF project Required scopes: bcf:read

id: integer
in path

A unique integer value identifying this project.

200 OK
BcfProject
Response Example (200 OK) 
{
  "id": "integer",
  "name": "string"
}
bcf

Update all fields of a BCF project

PUT /bcf/2.1/projects/{id}

Update all fields of a BCF project Required scopes: bcf:write

BcfProject

undefined

id: integer
in path

A unique integer value identifying this project.

Request Example
{
  "name": "string"
}
200 OK
BcfProject
Response Example (200 OK) 
{
  "id": "integer",
  "name": "string"
}

bcf

Export project's topics in bcf-xml format

GET /bcf/2.1/projects/{id}/export

Export project's topics in bcf-xml format Required scopes: bcf:read

topics: string
in query

topic guids to export, comma separated. Default = all

format: string
in query

topic format to export, comma separated. Default = all

id: integer
in path

A unique integer value identifying this project.

200 OK

The file

Retrieve all clouds

GET /cloud

Returns user's (or app's) clouds only

200 OK
Cloud
type
Cloud
Response Example (200 OK) 
[
  {
    "id": "integer",
    "name": "string",
    "features": [
      {
        "name": "string",
        "viewer_url": "string"
      }
    ],
    "creator": {
      "id": "integer",
      "email": "string (email)",
      "company": "string",
      "firstname": "string",
      "lastname": "string",
      "created_at": "string (date-time)",
      "updated_at": "string (date-time)",
      "cloud_role": "integer",
      "project_role": "integer"
    },
    "is_default": "boolean",
    "created_at": "string (date-time)",
    "updated_at": "string (date-time)"
  }
]

cloud

Invite a cloud administrator

POST /cloud/{cloud_pk}/invitation

Invite cloud administrators only. To invite in a project, see inviteProjectUser. You can't invite a user already in the cloud. Create multiple invitations of the same email in the same cloud will generate multiple invitation emails but not multiple invitation object Required scopes: org:manage

CloudInvitation

undefined

cloud_pk: string
in path

(no description)

Request Example
{
  "email": "string",
  "redirect_uri": "string"
}
201 Created
CloudInvitation
Response Example (201 Created) 
{
  "id": "integer",
  "email": "string",
  "redirect_uri": "string",
  "role": "integer"
}

project

Create a classification

POST /cloud/{cloud_pk}/project/{project_pk}/classification 
    Bulk create available.
                    You can either post an object or a list of objects.
                    Is you post a list, the response will be a list (in the same order) of created objects or of errors if any
                    If at least one create succeeded, the status code will be 201. If every create failed, the status code we'll be 400 with the list of errors
                
                If created classification already exists, it will not be duplicated and the previous one will be returned.
                You also can add a 'classification' filter on this endpoint. By ex: /classification?name='untec'. The name is case sensitive

Required scopes: ifc:write

Classification
cloud_pk: string
in path

(no description)

project_pk: string
in path

(no description)

Request Example
[
  {
    "name": "string",
    "notation": "string",
    "title": "string"
  }
]
200 OK
Classification
type
Classification
400 Bad Request

All creates failed: list of errors

Response Example (200 OK) 
[
  {
    "id": "integer",
    "name": "string",
    "notation": "string",
    "title": "string"
  }
]

GET /cloud/{cloud_pk}/project/{project_pk}/user/{id}

Each member of a project can see other members of the project Required scopes: cloud:read

cloud_pk: string
in path

(no description)

id: string
in path

(no description)

project_pk: string
in path

(no description)

200 OK
User
Response Example (200 OK) 
{
  "id": "integer",
  "email": "string (email)",
  "company": "string",
  "firstname": "string",
  "lastname": "string",
  "created_at": "string (date-time)",
  "updated_at": "string (date-time)",
  "cloud_role": "integer",
  "project_role": "integer"
}

Create an element in the model

POST /cloud/{cloud_pk}/project/{project_pk}/ifc/{ifc_pk}/element 
    Bulk create available.
    You can either post an object or a list of objects.
    Is you post a list, the response will be a list (in the same order) of created objects or of errors if any
    If at least one create succeeded, the status code will be 201. If every create failed, the status code we'll be 400 with the list of errors

ifc

Create one or many classifications to an element

POST /cloud/{cloud_pk}/project/{project_pk}/ifc/{ifc_pk}/element/{element_uuid}/classification 
    Bulk create available.
                    You can either post an object or a list of objects.
                    Is you post a list, the response will be a list (in the same order) of created objects or of errors if any
                    If at least one create succeeded, the status code will be 201. If every create failed, the status code we'll be 400 with the list of errors
                
                If classification created already exists, it will just be added to item's classifications and will not be duplicated

Delete many Property of a model

DELETE /cloud/{cloud_pk}/project/{project_pk}/ifc/{ifc_pk}/property/bulk_destroy 
    Bulk delete.
    You should send a list of ids in the body.
    These ids (or relations with these ids in case of many-to-many relation deletion) will be deleted

Required scopes: ifc:write

cloud_pk: string
in path

(no description)

ifc_pk: string
in path

(no description)

project_pk: string
in path

(no description)

204 No Content
ifc

Update all fields of many properties of a model

PUT /cloud/{cloud_pk}/project/{project_pk}/ifc/{ifc_pk}/property/bulk_update 
    Bulk update.
    Similar to update, but the body should be a list of objects to patch or put
    The response will be a list (in the same order) of updated objects or of errors if any
    If at least one update succeeded, the status code will be 200. If every update failed, the status code we'll be 400 with the list of errors

Required scopes: ifc:write

Create a PropertyDefinition on the model

POST /cloud/{cloud_pk}/project/{project_pk}/ifc/{ifc_pk}/propertydefinition 
    Bulk create available.
    You can either post an object or a list of objects.
    Is you post a list, the response will be a list (in the same order) of created objects or of errors if any
    If at least one create succeeded, the status code will be 201. If every create failed, the status code we'll be 400 with the list of errors

Create a PropertySet

POST /cloud/{cloud_pk}/project/{project_pk}/ifc/{ifc_pk}/propertyset 
    Bulk create available.
    You can either post an object or a list of objects.
    Is you post a list, the response will be a list (in the same order) of created objects or of errors if any
    If at least one create succeeded, the status code will be 201. If every create failed, the status code we'll be 400 with the list of errors

POST /cloud/{cloud_pk}/project/{project_pk}/ifc/{ifc_pk}/space 
    Bulk create available.
    You can either post an object or a list of objects.
    Is you post a list, the response will be a list (in the same order) of created objects or of errors if any
    If at least one create succeeded, the status code will be 201. If every create failed, the status code we'll be 400 with the list of errors

POST /cloud/{cloud_pk}/project/{project_pk}/ifc/{ifc_pk}/unit 
    Bulk create available.
    You can either post an object or a list of objects.
    Is you post a list, the response will be a list (in the same order) of created objects or of errors if any
    If at least one create succeeded, the status code will be 201. If every create failed, the status code we'll be 400 with the list of errors

ifc

Create a zone in the model

POST /cloud/{cloud_pk}/project/{project_pk}/ifc/{ifc_pk}/zone 
    Bulk create available.
    You can either post an object or a list of objects.
    Is you post a list, the response will be a list (in the same order) of created objects or of errors if any
    If at least one create succeeded, the status code will be 201. If every create failed, the status code we'll be 400 with the list of errors

Required scopes: ifc:write

User: object

id: integer
email: string (email) (at least 1 chars)
company: string
firstname: string (at least 1 chars)
lastname: string (at least 1 chars)
created_at: string (date-time)
updated_at: string (date-time)
cloud_role: integer
project_role: integer
Example
{
  "id": "integer",
  "email": "string (email)",
  "company": "string",
  "firstname": "string",
  "lastname": "string",
  "created_at": "string (date-time)",
  "updated_at": "string (date-time)",
  "cloud_role": "integer",
  "project_role": "integer"
}

Cloud: object

id: integer
name: string (1 to 256 chars)

Name of the cloud

features: Feature
Feature
creator: User
is_default: boolean
created_at: string (date-time)

Creation date

updated_at: string (date-time)

Date of the last update

Example
{
  "id": "integer",
  "name": "string",
  "features": [
    {
      "name": "string",
      "viewer_url": "string"
    }
  ],
  "creator": {
    "id": "integer",
    "email": "string (email)",
    "company": "string",
    "firstname": "string",
    "lastname": "string",
    "created_at": "string (date-time)",
    "updated_at": "string (date-time)",
    "cloud_role": "integer",
    "project_role": "integer"
  },
  "is_default": "boolean",
  "created_at": "string (date-time)",
  "updated_at": "string (date-time)"
}

CloudInvitation: object

id: integer
email: string (1 to 256 chars)

email of the user to invite

redirect_uri: string (1 to 512 chars)

User will be redirected to this uri when they accept the invitation

role: integer 100, 50
Example
{
  "id": "integer",
  "email": "string",
  "redirect_uri": "string",
  "role": "integer"
}

Project: object

id: integer
logo: string | null (uri)
cloud: Cloud
name: string (1 to 256 chars)

Name of the project

status: string A, D
created_at: string (date-time)

Creation date

updated_at: string (date-time)

Date of the last update

root_folder_id: string
property_permissions_enabled: boolean
Example
{
  "id": "integer",
  "logo": "string (uri)",
  "cloud": {
    "id": "integer",
    "name": "string",
    "features": [
      {
        "name": "string",
        "viewer_url": "string"
      }
    ],
    "creator": {
      "id": "integer",
      "email": "string (email)",
      "company": "string",
      "firstname": "string",
      "lastname": "string",
      "created_at": "string (date-time)",
      "updated_at": "string (date-time)",
      "cloud_role": "integer",
      "project_role": "integer"
    },
    "is_default": "boolean",
    "created_at": "string (date-time)",
    "updated_at": "string (date-time)"
  },
  "name": "string",
  "status": "string",
  "created_at": "string (date-time)",
  "updated_at": "string (date-time)",
  "root_folder_id": "string",
  "property_permissions_enabled": "boolean"
}

Document: object

id: integer
parent: integer | null
parent_id: integer
creator: integer | null
project: integer | null
name: string (1 to 512 chars)

Shown name of the file

file_name: string | null (up to 512 chars)

Full name of the file

description: string | null

Description of the file

file: string | null (uri)
size: integer | null 0 ≤ x ≤ 2147483647

Size of the file. The file may be compressed and show a smaller size

created_at: string (date-time)

Creation date

updated_at: string (date-time)

Date of the last update

ifc_id: string
Example
{
  "id": "integer",
  "parent": "integer",
  "parent_id": "integer",
  "creator": "integer",
  "project": "integer",
  "name": "string",
  "file_name": "string",
  "description": "string",
  "file": "string (uri)",
  "size": "integer",
  "created_at": "string (date-time)",
  "updated_at": "string (date-time)",
  "ifc_id": "string"
}

Unit: object

id: integer
type: string (at least 1 chars)

IfcDerivedUnit, IfcContextDependentUnit, IfcConversionBasedUnit, IfcSIUnit or IfcMonetaryUnit

name: string | null

Name of the unit (ex: DEGREE)

unit_type: string | null

IFC type of the unit or user defined type (ex: PLANEANGLEUNIT for DEGREE and RADIAN)

prefix: string | null

Litteral prefix for scale (ex: MILLI, KILO, etc..)

dimensions: number[] | null

List of 7 units dimensions

number
conversion_factor: number | null

Factor of conversion and base unit id (ex: DEGREE from RADIAN with factor 0.0174532925199433)

conversion_baseunit: Unit
elements: string | null

List of constitutive unit elements by id with corresponding exponent (ex: [meterID/1, secondID/-1] for velocity)

Example
{
  "id": "integer",
  "type": "string",
  "name": "string",
  "unit_type": "string",
  "prefix": "string",
  "dimensions": [
    "number"
  ],
  "conversion_factor": "number",
  "conversion_baseunit": {
    "id": "integer",
    "type": "string",
    "name": "string",
    "unit_type": "string",
    "prefix": "string",
    "dimensions": [
      "number"
    ],
    "conversion_factor": "number",
    "conversion_baseunit": {
